XCryIfuBMK0TIlbSbDFaOHa9ABkl7zq7XKyvBBspGrkh1dqluxX_TPyYKi7k], goes in dept=
h if you=E2=80=99re interested in learning more.)
Byrne=E2=80=99s point was that when everyone is going after the same custom=
er via the same channels with similar products, the company that can convin=
ce itself that it can make more money per customer will pay more to acquire=
 those customers. The most optimistic company gets the most customers, even=
 if the optimism was misplaced. If they=E2=80=99re too optimistic, they los=
e money. The more accurate companies lose customers. Everyone loses.=C2=A0
In the beginning of a new industry, when there=E2=80=99s less infrastructur=
e and less competition, the battleground is product: can you actually build=
 the thing you say you=E2=80=99re building? Over time, as a space matures a=
nd the building blocks become standardized, the battleground moves to audie=
nce. When anyone can sell some version of the same thing, acquiring custome=
rs becomes the hardest part. That=E2=80=99s why Google and Facebook make so=
 much money. As more competitors vie for the same customers, CAC goes up, a=
nd companies need to either accept a lower CAC/LTV ratio, or increase LTV b=
y increasing prices, cross-selling more products, or improving retention.=
=C2=A0
This is true across industries, and it=E2=80=99s particularly true in consu=
mer fintech. There are only so many financial products that most people buy=
